      '\n- Any two of the following (AT LEAST ONE for phosphorus and ONE for sulfur):\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ sulfur is found in protein and not in DNA\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ 35S is used to label protein\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ phosphorus is found in DNA and not in protein\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ 32P is used to label DNA\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>2 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \n35S is used because sulphur is found in protein and not in DNA ($\\checkmark$), and  32P is used because phosphorus is found in DNA and not protein ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any one of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ X-ray crystallography OR diffraction (by Rosalind Franklin)\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ paper chromatography (by Erwin Chargaff)\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>1 mark maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nAnother technological development used was X-ray diffraction ($\\checkmark$) by Rosalind Franklin which provided evidence that DNA has a helical shape.\n\n\n\n- \n  - \n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ 35S OR radioactively labelled protein was found in the supernatant OR not found in the pellet OR no radioactivity detected in bacteria infected with viruses labelled with 35S\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ 32P OR radioactively labelled DNA was found in the pellet OR not found in the supernatant OR radioactivity was detected in bacteria infected with viruses labelled with 32P\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>2 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nThe results from the Hershey-Chase experiment showed that 35S, used to label protein, was found in the supernatant ($\\checkmark$), and the 32P, used to label DNA, was found in the pellet ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- \n  - Any two of the following:\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the four nitrogenous bases are A, T, G, C OR adenine, thymine, guanine, cytosine \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ polypeptides are coded for by genes OR a sequence of nucleotides \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ three nitrogenous bases OR codon OR triplet of bases, code for a specific amino acid OR start OR stop <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ degenerative code OR several codons can code for one amino acid <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ DNA as a template OR antisense strand to form mRNA strand\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ complementary base pairing between DNA nucleotides and RNA nucleotides OR between codons on mRNA and amino acid\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ mRNA is used as template to form polypeptide chains\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>2 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nPolypeptides are coded for by genes ($\\checkmark$) made up of a specific sequence of nucleotides. A nucleotide consists of a ribose sugar, a phosphate group and one of four nitrogenous bases - adenine, guanine, cytosine and thymine ($\\checkmark$).  DNA  is used as a template to form the mRNA strand ($\\checkmark$). A triplet of bases, a codon, along the mRNA strand codes for a specific amino acid ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any three of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ DNA tightly wraps around a core of eight histone proteins\t <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ held together by an additional histone protein OR H1 linker protein\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ H1 histone proteins binds the nucleosomes together to form a 30 nm chromatin fibre \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ long DNA molecules are packed into a small space \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the negatively charged DNA is attracted to the positively charged histones \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ form structures called nucleosomes\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ nucleosomes are attached to other nucleosomes by linker DNA \t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nDNA coils tightly around a core of eight histone proteins ($\\checkmark$) which are held together by H1 histone proteins ($\\checkmark$) to form structures known as nucleosomes ($\\checkmark$). The nucleosomes are bundled together to form the 30nm fibre chromatin ($\\checkmark$).\n',
