      'The graph shows the results of an experiment by Hershey and Chase. Bacteria (E. coli) were infected with virus particles labelled with either (radioactive phosphorus) $\\ce{^{32}P}$ or (radioactive sulfur) $\\ce{^{35}S}$. A blender was used to remove attached viruses from the bacterial cells and samples collected from the suspension were centrifuged to record the percentage of isotope remaining in the cells. \n$\\text{\\textquotedblleft}$infected bacteria” refers to the percentage of live bacteria that survived the blending process.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/8ed5cb9a-b4cc-48f2-9a43-a583465327c3/images/6586b9a3-accb-446e-a5a0-30c7e2670160/Edit.png)\n\n\n[© Revision Village 2024. Created with BioRender.com]\n\nWhich of the following statements explain(s) why the extracellular $\\ce{^{32}P}$ increased as the running time in the blender increased?\n\n\n- I.When bacteriophages infect bacteria, not all viral particles successfully inject their DNA into the host cells. Some phages remain attached to the cell surface or fail to transfer their DNA.II.During blending, the infected bacteria take up more $\\ce{^{32}P}$.III.During blending, some of the infected bacterial cells are lysed (the reason the $\\text{\\textquotedblleft}$infected bacteria” percentage decreases). The lysed cells release their $\\ce{^{32}P}$.\n\n\n\n\n- A.$\\hspace{1em}$ I and III\n- B.$\\hspace{1em}$ I and II only\n- C.$\\hspace{1em}$ III only\n- D.$\\hspace{1em}$ I, II and III\n',
