      'The image below shows a short fragment of the DNA molecule.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/e629bb8b-e8a1-4fbb-98c8-3e6f92616fa2/images/340a17d6-8f7c-4284-b384-26100ff9f334/BI1048A.png)\n\n\n[Source: Adapted from User: Madprime. (2010, March). File: DNA chemical structure jp.svg. Wikimedia Commons. Retrieved May 15, 2022, from https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File: DNA_chemical_structure_jp.svg. Copyright under CC-SA 3.0]\n\n- Suggest one possible problem that could arise if DNA consisted of two parallel strands instead of two antiparallel strands.  \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n- State one place where DNA is found in cells. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n- Compare and contrast the structure of DNA and RNA.\t\t<span class="marks">[5]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Any one of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ no hydrogen bonding between base pairs\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ two strands are not held together OR no double-stranded DNA\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ two strands would be geometrically the same, thus unable to combine \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>1 mark maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nIf DNA were made of two parallel strands, both strands would be oriented in the same 3’ to 5’ direction. Since the DNA strand is tilted and not straight, that would mean that two DNA strands would not be able to combine ($\\checkmark$) to form a double helix.\n\n\n\n- \n\n$\\hspace{1em}$ $\\ce{ -> }$ nucleus OR nucleoid OR mitochondria OR chloroplasts OR plasmids\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>1 mark maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n$\\hspace{1em}$ $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \n$\\hspace{1em}$ One place where DNA is found in the cell is in the nucleus ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n- Any five of the following (there must be at least one similarity and one difference given to gain full marks):\n  Similarities: \n$\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH DNA and RNA are composed of nucleotides OR sugar, phosphate AND base <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH DNA and RNA contain four types of nitrogenous bases <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH DNA and RNA have covalent bonds holding nucleotides together <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH DNA and RNA exhibit base pairing OR complementary bases are connected through hydrogen bonds OR have hydrogen bonds between the complementary nitrogenous bases <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH DNA and RNA have a backbone made up of alternating sugar and phosphate groups <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH DNA and RNA are polymers, composed of repeating monomer units OR nucleotides, linked together in a chain <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  \n  Differences: \n$\\ce{ -> }$ DNA contains deoxyribose sugar WHEREAS RNA contains ribose  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ DNA contains the nitrogenous bases adenine, thymine, cytosine and  guanine OR ATCG WHEREAS RNA contains adenine, uracil, cytosine and guanine OR AUCG, OR in DNA adenine pairs with thymine and cytosine pairs with guanine WHEREAS in RNA adenine pairs with uracil and cytosine pairs with guanine  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ DNA typically consists of two (antiparallel) strands WHEREAS RNA is usually single-stranded <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ in DNA adenine pairs with thymine and cytosine pairs with guanine WHEREAS in RNA adenine pairs with uracil and cytosine pairs with guanine  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ DNA typically forms a double-stranded helical structure with base pairing between the two strands  WHEREAS RNA can fold into complex secondary structures due to intra-strand base pairing, creating loops, stems, and hairpin structures <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>5 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nBoth DNA and RNA are made up of nucleotides ($\\checkmark$), however, the sugar in DNA is deoxyribose, whilst that in RNA is ribose ($\\checkmark$). Both DNA and RNA contain four different nitrogenous bases ($\\checkmark$), however, DNA contains adenine, guanine, cytosine and thymine, whilst RNA contains uracil instead of thymine ($\\checkmark$). Both DNA and RNA are polymers of nucleotides ($\\checkmark$) held together by covalent bonds ($\\checkmark$) between the sugar of one nucleotide and a phosphate group of the next, however, DNA is typically double-stranded, and RNA is typically single-stranded ($\\checkmark$).\n',
