    content:
      '\n- Distinguish between RNA and DNA.\t \t<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Explain the importance of orientation and directionality of DNA and RNA. \t\t <span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Describe how the Hershey and Chase experiment demonstrated that DNA carries the genetic information .   \t<span class="marks">[8]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Any three of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$  RNA is single-stranded  WHEREAS DNA is double-stranded\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ RNA has a variety of shapes WHEREAS DNA is a double helix\t <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ RNA contains ribose sugar  WHEREAS DNA contains deoxyribose\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ RNA contains the nitrogenous base uracil OR U WHEREAS DNA contains thymine OR T <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ RNA only contains permanent genetic code in RNA viruses WHEREAS DNA contains permanent genetic code in all cells (except red blood cells)\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nRNA is a single stranded molecule containing ribose sugar and uracil as one of its four nitrogenous bases. DNA on the other hand is double-stranded ($\\checkmark$), contains deoxyribose instead of ribose sugar ($\\checkmark$), and has thymine instead of uracil ($\\checkmark$) as one of its four nitrogenous bases. DNA forms a regular double helix, whereas RNA can form different shapes  ($\\checkmark$) depending on its role, such as the clover-shaped tRNA and long-stranded mRNA.\n\n\n\n- Any four of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ 5’ OR 5 prime end  refers to the end with a phosphate group bound to the 5th carbon of the deoxyribose OR pentose sugar, but not bound to another nucleotide, the 3’ OR 3 prime end refers to the end where the 3rd carbon of the deoxyribose OR pentose sugar is not bound to another nucleotide\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ DNA has antiparallel strands OR one strand is in the 5’ to 3’ direction, and another strand is in the 3’ to 5’ strand \t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ single DNA strand is tilted; therefore, two DNA strands can only bind together if they are in antiparallel orientation\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ in DNA replication, one lagging strand and one leading strand are produced\t <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ in DNA replication DNA polymerase only adds free nucleotides to the 3’ end of the growing DNA strand OR adds free nucleotides in the 5’ to 3’ direction\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ in transcription RNA polymerase can only add nucleotides in the 5’ to 3’ direction to form mRNA\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ translation must start nearest to the 5’ end of the mRNA\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>4 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nBoth RNA and DNA have directionality they have a 5’ and 3’ end. The 5’ end refers to the end with a phosphate group attached to carbon 5 of the deoxyribose, but not attached to another nucleotide, the 3’ end refers to the end where carbon 3 of the deoxyribose is not attached to another nucleotide ($\\checkmark$). DNA forms a double helix with antiparallel strands ($\\checkmark$). During replication DNA polymerase can only add free nucleotides in the 5’ to 3’ direction ($\\checkmark$). During transcription RNA polymerase can only add nucleotides in the 5’ to 3’ direction ($\\checkmark$) to form a strand of mRNA. Translation of the mRNA must start at the 5’ end ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any eight of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ bacteriophages OR phage virus was used \t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ bacteriophage contains an inner core that has DNA and a protein coat\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ experiments tested the hypothesis that DNA and not protein carries the genetic information\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ bacteriophage OR virus can attach to the surface of bacterial cell OR host and inject substance into the cell\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ substance contains information for bacteria cell OR host to duplicate OR produce more bacteriophages OR viruses\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ bacteriophages OR virus were labeled with radioactive phosphorus (32P) and radioactive sulfur (35S) OR 32P was incorporated into DNA core and 35S was incorporated into protein coat\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ phosphorus is found only in DNA and not protein\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ sulfur is found only in protein and not DNA\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ Escherichia coli OR bacterial cells were infected with bacteriophage OR virus  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ used centrifuge to separate bacteriophage OR virus from bacteria\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ virus in liquid OR supernatant did not contain radioactive 32P but bacterial sediment OR pellet contained radioactive 32P\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ 32P DNA entered the bacteria OR host cell for replication\t  \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ virus in liquid OR supernatant contained radioactive 35S but bacterial sediment OR pellet did not contain radioactive 35S\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ 35S protein structure did not enter the bacteria OR host cell for replication \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ genetic material needs to enter the bacterial cell in order to produce new viruses     <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>8 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nHershey and Chase\'s experiment was conducted to investigate whether DNA or protein carries the genetic material. In their experiment, they used bacteriophages ($\\checkmark$) to infect bacteria cells. Bacteriophage contains an outer coat made of protein and an inner core containing DNA ($\\checkmark$) which makes it suitable for comparing DNA and protein. The bacteriophage can then attach itself to the surface of the bacteria cell and inject the substance ($\\checkmark$) which carries important genetic information into the bacteria cell.\n  The bacteriophages were then cultured under two different conditions — one was incorporated with a radioactive phosphorus isotope, 32P and another with a radioactive sulfur isotope, 35S ($\\checkmark$). Radioactive elements 32P and 35S were used because phosphorus is found in the DNA structure but absent in protein ($\\checkmark$), whereas sulfur, is found in the protein structure but absent in the DNA ($\\checkmark$) structure.\n  The bacteria cells were then cultured together with the bacteriophages and were infected with the bacteriophages ($\\checkmark$). After centrifugation, it was found that the pellets containing bacteria cultured with the radioactive 32P bacteriophages contained radioactivity, whereas the bacteriophage protein coats in the supernatant didn’t ($\\checkmark$).  The pellets containing the bacteria cultured with the radioactive 35S bacteriophages did not contain any radioactivity, whereas the bacteriophage protein coats in the supernatant did ($\\checkmark$). These provided evidence that DNA labelled with the 32P entered the bacteria cells, whereas the protein which was labelled with the 35S did not ($\\checkmark$) enter the bacteria cells.\n\n\nA quality mark is awarded if each part of the question (a, b, c) is answered to earn at least half of the points available, answers do not require re-reading to be understood, and there are almost no errors and little irrelevant information.  <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n',
