      'Haem is the non-protein, iron-binding component found in haemoglobin.  Haem and chlorophyll are similar in structure but chlorophyll contains a magnesium ion instead of iron. The biochemical pathways that make haem and chlorophyll involve enzymes that are highly conserved across many distantly related species.  The diagram shows an amino acid sequence alignment for part of one such enzyme, delta-aminolevulinate dehydratase. Each amino acid is represented by a single-letter code.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/ead7be09-9196-4de7-99cd-8c7fad3ab982/images/dea9dbde-ae55-4c23-a6af-855ba79a2b83/Edit1.png)\n\n\n[Source: Alignment created with and adapted from Cobalt with Refseq and Genbank sequences from National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI)[Internet]. Bethesda (MD): National Library of Medicine (US), National Center for Biotechnology Information; [1988] – [cited 2024]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/]\n\n\n- The diagram suggests that certain metabolic pathways are conserved across diverse organisms. Discuss how these conserved pathways provide evidence for LUCA.\t  <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- Suggest two environmental conditions found in hydrothermal vents that may have facilitated the evolution of early metabolic pathways.\t\t<span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- Explain how genomic analysis can be used to estimate the time period in which the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) existed.\t\t<span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- Scientists discovered a bacterial enzyme with a significantly different amino acid sequence from its human counterpart but nearly identical function.  Suggest possible reasons why this function is conserved despite sequence divergence.\t <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- any two of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ conserved metabolic pathways OR similar enzymes in conserved pathways suggest a shared evolutionary origin OR fundamental processes like glycolysis OR ATP synthesis OR protein translation are found in all life forms\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ highly conserved pathways demonstrate biochemical efficiency favoured in natural selection OR strong selective pressure \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the lack of any other widespread metabolic mechanisms suggests competition and extinction of other forms of life\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>2 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nMany fundamental processes like glycolysis are conserved across all known life forms ($\\checkmark$).  This indicates a shared evolutionary origin and supports the idea of LUCA (the last universal common ancestor).  The lack of other metabolic mechanisms suggests that they may have existed in early species but were outcompeted and became extinct ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- any two of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ heat energy to increase the rate of chemical reactions\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ high pressure at thermal vents stabilised complex chemical reactions that could not occur in less extreme environments\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ minerals to serve as catalysts promoting biochemical reactions\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ mineral-rich vents may have mimicked cell membranes, concentrating molecules and enabling the development of metabolic pathways\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ proton gradients OR pH gradient for ATP synthesis via chemiosmosis\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ energy sources such as hydrogen OR methane OR sulfide gases as electron donors for metabolic reactions\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ highly reduced compounds from vents coming into contact with the ocean’s oxidised compounds provided redox gradients driving early metabolism\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ lack of oxygen prevented oxidative damage to early organic molecules OR supported anaerobic metabolism development\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  <span class="marks">[<strong>2 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nThe heat and high-pressure environment of the hydrothermal vents may have enabled the evolution of metabolic pathways as heat energy increases the rate of chemical reactions ($\\checkmark$) and high pressure stabilises complex chemical reactions ($\\checkmark$) that may not have been able to occur in less extreme environments.\n\n\n\n- any two of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ phylogenetic trees constructed from genomic data illustrate evolutionary relationships\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ comparing conserved genetic sequences helps infer evolutionary timelines, as more conserved sequences indicate older ancestry\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ genomic evidence combined with other evidence OR fossils helps establish LUCA’s timefram\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ molecular clocks estimate divergence time by assuming mutations accumulate at a constant rate\n<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ highly conserved ribosomal RNA OR rRNA sequences are useful for estimating divergence events\n<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  <span class="marks">[<strong>2 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nPhylogenetic trees, constructed from genomic data, illustrate evolutionary relationships, helping estimate when LUCA existed by identifying divergence points ($\\checkmark$)  Molecular clocks further refine this by comparing genetic differences and applying a known mutation rate to infer the timing of common ancestry ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- any two of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ proteins with different primary sequences can fold into similar three-dimensional conformations OR structures\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ an enzyme\'s function depends on its 3-D structure\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ variations in sites other than the active site may not affect function\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ convergence in evolution can lead to functionally similar enzymes despite a difference in sequence\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ some amino acid substitutions are neutral and do not alter protein folding OR stability OR active site configuration\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ other structural adaptations OR flexible binding sites OR other suitable named adaptation allow variations in sequence without affecting overall enzyme function\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>2 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nProteins with different primary sequences fold into similar three-dimensional structures ($\\checkmark$). Since an enzyme’s function depends on its 3D structure, especially the shape of the active site ($\\checkmark$), as long as it has a similar structure, it should be able to perform a similar function ($\\checkmark$).\n',
