      "Below is a diagram of swan necked flasks, containing boiled broth, which are similar to those used by Pasteur in his experiments on spontaneous generation. The air access and neck shape differ between them.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/fa7cb3ca-ef45-4a81-8a5f-53a77f8d6f8a/images/ce69f2c0-818b-4b45-9d4a-985c0ab6ed48/BI1444%20fig1.png)\n\n\r\n[©Revision Village 2024. Created with BioRender.com]\n\nHow did Pasteur's experiments with swan-necked flasks provide convincing evidence to falsify the concept of spontaneous generation?\n\n\n- I. $\\hspace{1em}$ Broth in flask X grew cloudy due to dust and microbes being trapped in the neck, suggesting that even filtered air can induce microbial growth.\n- II. $\\hspace{.7em}$ Broth in flask Y remained clear, indicating no spontaneous microbial growth, as the sealed environment prevented any external contamination.\n- III. $\\hspace{.4em}$ Broth in flask Z remained clear, proving that exposure to air alone does not lead to microbial growth.\n\n\n\n\n- A. $\\hspace{1em}$ I only\n- B. $\\hspace{1em}$ II only\n- C. $\\hspace{1em}$ I and II only\n- D. $\\hspace{1em}$ I, II and III\n",
