    markScheme:
      '\n- Any three of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ nutrition by diffusion through cell membrane OR engulfment OR phagocytosis OR endocytosis OR photosynthesis OR digestion by enzymes in vacuoles\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ movement by cilia OR flagella OR pseudopodia\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ excretion by  simple diffusion OR active transport OR exocytosis OR contractile vacuoles OR  vacuoles storing OR isolating waste before removal\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nUnicellular organisms carry out the processes of life in varying ways. They can carry out nutrition by engulfing the nutrients ($\\checkmark$) from their surroundings, they can move using flagella  ($\\checkmark$), and they can remove wastes from the cell by simple diffusion  ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Diagram must include four of the following labels and annotations:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ outer membrane protective barrier OR contains transport proteins that allow specific molecules to enter the mitochondrion\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ inner membrane OR cristae increase surface area for reactions OR contains proteins essential for reactions OR ATP production <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ DNA encodes genes essential for mitochondrial functioning\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ 70S ribosomes for synthesis of proteins required by mitochondrion\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ matrix contains enzymes for chemical reactions\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ intermembrane space - allows build-up of protons OR ion gradient for ATP synthesis OR chemiosmosis OR contains enzymes for chemical reactions\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ clear drawing with no sketchy lines and of suitable size \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>5 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$:\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/ba177021-8efc-4ac3-8984-af65f603bc24/images/51530aa5-3ec2-45cc-8701-1d4b4fd4ec74/BI1049.png)\n\n\n[© Revision village 2022]\n\n\n\n- Any seven of the following (must contain at least one similarity and/or one difference):\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH E.coli and palisade mesophyll cells have cell OR plasma membranes\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH E.coli and palisade mesophyll cells have cytoplasm \t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH E.coli and palisade mesophyll cells have a cell wall\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH E.coli and palisade mesophyll cells contain ribosomes \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ E.coli cell wall is made up of peptidoglycan WHEREAS palisade mesophyll cell walls are made of cellulose\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ palisade mesophyll cells have a compartmentalised structure WHEREAS E.coli do not\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ palisade mesophyll cells have 80S ribosomes WHEREAS E.coli have 70S\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ palisade mesophyll cells have nuclei WHEREAS E.coli have a nucleoid\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ E.coli can have plasmids OR circular DNA WHEREAS palisade mesophyll cells have linear DNA\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ E.coli have external structures such as flagella OR pili BUT palisade mesophyll cells do not \t\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ palisade mesophyll cells have membrane bound organelles such as golgi apparatus, rough endoplasmic reticulum, chloroplasts, mitochondria WHEREAS E.coli do not\t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>7 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nPalisade mesophyll cells and E.coli both have cell membranes ($\\checkmark$) and cytoplasm ($\\checkmark$). They also both can have cell walls ($\\checkmark$), however the cell wall in E.coli is composed of peptidoglycan, whereas the cell wall in palisade mesophyll cells is composed of cellulose ($\\checkmark$). Palisade mesophyll cells are full of membrane bound organelles such as the golgi apparatus, which gives them a compartmentalised structure, whereas E.coli do not have a compartmentalised structure or membrane bound organelles ($\\checkmark$). Both palisade mesophyll cells and E.coli have ribosomes ($\\checkmark$), but E.coli have 70S ribosomes and palisade mesophyll cells have 80S ribosomes  ($\\checkmark$). DNA is also stored differently in palisade mesophyll cells and E.coli. Palisade mesophyll cells store their DNA inside the nucleus and it has a linear structure, whereas E.coli have DNA floating freely in the cytoplasm as a nucleoid ($\\checkmark$) and can sometimes contain extra DNA in the form of a plasmid ($\\checkmark$). E.coli can also have external structures such as pili or flagella ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\nA quality mark is awarded if each part of the question (a, b, c) is answered to earn at least half of the points available, answers do not require re-reading to be understood, and there are almost no errors and little irrelevant information. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n',
