    content:
      '\n- Distinguish between the structure and location of chromosomes found in eukaryotes and prokaryotes.\t\t\t<span class="marks">[5]</span>\n\n- Describe the stages of meiosis and how genetically unique, haploid gametes are created during the process.\t<span class="marks">[7]</span>\n\n- Explain the information that can be deduced from a human karyogram.\t\t<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Any five of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ eukaryotic chromosomes are found in the nucleus WHEREAS prokaryotic chromosomes are found in the nucleoid region OR chromosomes of eukaryotes are contained within a membrane WHEREAS prokaryotic chromosomes are not membrane bound \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotes have a circular chromosome WHEREAS eukaryotes have linear chromosomes\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotes typically have one chromosome WHEREAS eukaryotes typically have multiple chromosomes\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ in eukaryotic chromosomes, DNA is associated with histone proteins WHEREAS prokaryotic chromosomes do not contain histones\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic chromosomes do not contain centromeres WHEREAS eukaryotic chromosomes do <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ prokaryotic chromosomes do not contain telomeres WHEREAS eukaryotic chromosomes do\t <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ eukaryotic chromosomes carry more genetic information OR DNA OR genes THAN prokaryotic chromosomes\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>5 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nEukaryotic chromosomes are found in the nucleus whereas prokaryotic chromosomes are found in the nucleoid region ($\\checkmark$). Prokaryotes typically contain one, circular chromosome ($\\checkmark$)  whereas eukaryotes  have multiple, linear chromosomes ($\\checkmark$). Prokaryotic chromosomes do not contain centromeres and telomeres ($\\checkmark$), whereas eukaryotic chromosomes do ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any seven of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ all the DNA in a cell is replicated during interphase\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ so cells are diploid OR contain homologous chromosomes when they enter meiosis\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ homologous chromosomes pair AND become visible OR condense  in prophase I\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ crossing over occurs between the non-sister chromatids of homologous chromosomes during prophase I\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ homologous chromosomes are moved to the equator of the cell by spindle microtubules AND randomly orientated OR independently assorted in metaphase I <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ homologous chromosomes are pulled to opposite sides of the cell by spindle microtubules in anaphase I\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ one diploid cell is split into two haploid cells <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ chromatids condense OR become visible during prophase II\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ pairs of sister chromatids are moved to the equator of the cell by spindle microtubules during metaphase II AND randomly orientated OR independently assorted\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ pairs of sister chromatids are separated by spindle fibres in anaphase II\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ nuclear membrane reforms in telophase II AND four haploid cells are formed from the two haploid cells of \tmeiosis \t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ crossing over during prophase I AND independent assortment OR random alignment of homologous chromosomes in metaphase I OR metaphase II result in unique gametes\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>7 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nAll of the DNA in a cell is replicated during interphase ($\\checkmark$), so cells are diploid when they enter meiosis ($\\checkmark$). Homologous chromosomes pair up, become visible ($\\checkmark$) and crossing over of non-sister chromatids occur during prophase I ($\\checkmark$). Then, homologous chromosomes are moved to the equator of the cell by spindle microtubules and randomly orientated during metaphase I ($\\checkmark$). Homologous chromosomes are pulled to the opposite poles of the cell by spindle fibres in anaphase I ($\\checkmark$) and one diploid cell is split into two haploid cells during telophase I ($\\checkmark$). The cells then enter meiosis II. The pairs of sister chromatids are independently assorted to form a single line along the equator of the cell, in metaphase II ($\\checkmark$). During anaphase II the centromeres split and the sister chromatids are pulled to opposite poles of the cell ($\\checkmark$). In telophase II the nuclear membrane reforms around the chromosomes, and after cytokinesis, 4 new haploid, non-identical,  daughter cells are formed from the 2 haploid cells that resulted from meiosis I ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any three of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ a karyogram is an image showing the positions of centromeres and banding patterns of stained OR dyed homologous chromosomes ordered by decreasing length\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ biological sex determined by XX and XY OR sex chromosomes\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ whether non-disjunction has occurred is determined by the presence or absence of chromosome (s)\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ presence of chromosomal abnormalities (such as breakages or translocation) determined by the banding pattern OR size of chromosome\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ indication of chromosome disorders such as Down syndrome, which is caused by trisomy 21<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nA karyogram is an image showing the positions of centromeres and banding patterns of stained homologous chromosomes ordered by decreasing length ($\\checkmark$). A karyogram can be used to deduce biological sex ($\\checkmark$) or the presence of chromosomal abnormalities ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\nA quality mark is awarded if each part of the question (a, b, c) is answered to earn at least half of the points available, answers do not require re-reading to be understood, and there are almost no errors and little irrelevant information. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n',
