      '\n- Any three of the following (students must give at least one similarity and one difference to achieve full marks):\n  Similarities\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH concepts seek to define a species\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH concepts acknowledge that there can be variation within species\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ BOTH concepts are connected to the broader concept of evolution\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  Differences\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the biological species concept defines a species as a group of organisms which can interbreed to produce fertile offspring, WHEREAS the morphological concept defines a species as a group of organisms with shared traits\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ Mayr proposed the biological species concept WHEREAS the morphological concept was proposed by Linnaeus\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the morphological species concept was proposed before the biological species concept    <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the morphological species concept is applicable to sexual and asexual organisms, WHEREAS the biological species concept is applicable only to sexually reproducing organisms \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the biological species concept reflects the evolutionary relationship OR speciation OR gene flow, WHEREAS the morphological species concept may not represent genetic relatedness or evolutionary relationships <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>3 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nBoth concepts are used to define species ($\\checkmark$), but Mayr proposed the biological species concept, whereas the morphological concept was proposed by Linnaeus ($\\checkmark$). The morphological concept also came first ($\\checkmark$). The biological species concept defines a species as a group of organisms that can interbreed to produce fertile offspring; however, the morphological concept defines a species as a group of organisms with shared traits ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any five of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the morphological species concept cannot be applied to species that show variation due to reproductive isolation OR the morphological concept cannot be applied to species with different forms OR polymorphism OR named example of a species with different forms \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the morphological species concept does not take into account DNA OR genetic information   <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the biological species concept is defined in terms of sexual reproduction HOWEVER, not all organisms reproduce sexually \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ example of species that reproduce asexually, e.g. budding in yeast OR horizontal gene transfer in bacteria \t\t\t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the biological species concept relies on the ability to observe and study interbreeding in real-time, which is not possible with extinct species OR fossilised organisms \t\t\t <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ some different species can interbreed and produce viable offspring, but these hybrids might have reduced fitness or be sterile, which challenges the clear-cut boundaries proposed by the biological species concept \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ convergent evolution can make it difficult to accurately group organisms based solely on morphological characteristics \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ rapid evolution and morphological changes in response to the environment might make individuals appear distinct, even if they share a recent common ancestor, which challenges the reliability of morphological traits as indicators of species relationships \t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>5 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nThe biological species concept defines a species as a group of organisms that can interbreed to produce fertile offspring, however, not all species reproduce sexually ($\\checkmark$), for example, yeast reproduce asexually by budding ($\\checkmark$). It also relies on the ability to see species interbreeding, which cannot be done with extinct species or fossils ($\\checkmark$). The morphological concept defines a species as a group of organisms with shared traits, however, due to variation caused by reproductive isolation and mutation, not all members of a species look the same ($\\checkmark$). In addition, rapid evolution might make individuals appear distinctly related when in fact, they shared a recent common ancestor. This could make the morphological species concept less reliable ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\n\n- Any seven of the following:\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ species can be defined as a group of organisms that are capable of interbreeding to produce fertile offspring\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ species usually share the same number of chromosomes \t <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ species usually share identical karyotypes \t\t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ example of chromosome complement of a species, e.g. humans have 46 chromosomes \t      <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the chromosome complement of a species can vary due to genetic conditions such as Down syndrome \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the size genome of a species can vary within a species   <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ the base sequence of the genome can vary within a species \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ due to mutations or single-nucleotide polymorphisms <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ homologous genes OR similarities in gene pathways OR similarities in the functions of genes can be found between species that share evolutionary origins \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ species-specific genes are not found in other closely related species \t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  $\\ce{ -> }$ horizontal gene transfer between different species, often through mechanisms like viral infections or symbiotic relationships, leads to the acquisition of genes in the recipient that may not be shared by other members of the species \t\t<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n<span class="marks">[<strong>7 marks maximum</strong>]</span>\n\n  $\\underline{\\textrm{Sample answer}}$: \nAccording to the biological species concept, a species can be defined as a group of organisms that are capable of interbreeding to produce fertile offspring ($\\checkmark$). They can produce fertile offspring as a species usually have the same chromosome number ($\\checkmark$), for example, in humans, this is 46 ($\\checkmark$) unless genetic conditions such as Down syndrome affect their karyotype ($\\checkmark$). The size of a species\' genome can vary slightly within a species ($\\checkmark$), as can the base sequence of the genome ($\\checkmark$) and these are both due to mutations ($\\checkmark$).\n\n\nA quality mark is awarded if each part of the question (a, b, c) is answered to earn at least half of the points available, answers do not require re-reading to be understood, and there are almost no errors and little irrelevant information. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n',
