      'The graph below shows Biodiversity Intactness, a long-term indicator that measures how much original biodiversity remains within terrestrial communities on the continents, based on levels from around 1500 A.D., when records began.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/af00fec2-0075-40c9-8a41-072c06650376/images/1ad75b4e-1e66-416a-87f8-4d878e1c4179/BI2808%20-%20Bi2813%20A4.2%20PQ%20MCQ%20and%20SAQ%20PhilCh.jpeg.JPEG)\n\n\n[Source: adapted from WWF (2024) Living Planet Report 2024 – A System in\nPeril. WWF, Gland, Switzerland http://bit.ly/4jzPxrE. Retrieved 30 April 2025, Public Domain]\n\n\n- \n  - Using data from the graph, compare and contrast biodiversity in Asia and Europe.  <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n  - Suggest reasons for the difference(s) you highlighted in part (a) (i)   <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n\n- Outline two reasons why the graph might give an inexact picture of global biodiversity loss.  <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- Certain Asian species, including the Chinese Crocodile Lizard (Shinisaurus crocodilurus), have been selected for the EDGE of Existence programme in Asia, whereas another endangered species, the Asian elephant (Elephas maximus), is not on the EDGE of Existence list. Suggest why.  <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n',
